Study 1b mirrored all procedures described for Study 1a, but Study 1b participants viewed a different selection of stimuli. Specifically, for each Study 1b participant, six stimuli showed non-alcoholic drinks (either from professional or non-professional sources; the focal stimuli in this study). In addition, Study 1b participants viewed 6 stimuli showing alcoholic drinks (stimuli of non-interest in this study) in order to create an experience comparable to that of Study 1a participants. For each participant, the non-alcohol stimuli were randomly chosen out of a total of 30 non-alcohol stimuli. The alcohol stimuli were chosen out of the set of 76 alcohol-related stimuli that constitute a subset of the alcohol-related stimuli used in Study 1a. All stimuli were shown evenly across participants. Each non-alcohol stimulus was rated by an average of $\Sexpr{round(s$m,2)}$ (SD = $\Sexpr{round(s$s,2)}$) participants.


